  urldate = {2024-10-09},
  abstract = {Flat optical components (metasurfaces) made from artificial electromagnetic materials (metamaterials) have opened new possibilities for the manipulation of electromagnetic waves within compact multifunctional devices. This field encompasses the development of individual optical elements and their integration into systems for use in real-world applications, especially in optical information processing, light detection and ranging (LiDAR), augmented or virtual reality, and biological imaging. This comprehensive Review highlights advances in the use of flat optics in analog computational information processing and imaging applications and emphasizes their fundamental role in transfer function engineering. The natural synergy between flat optics and computational technologies is described in relation to advanced imaging and microscopy solutions that have the potential for simultaneous information acquisition and processing. An outlook on future developments, including critical insights for both newcomers and experts in this field, is also provided.},
